Dialogue:
Boat leaves in ten minutes, Dad.
It is with profound praise and gratitude that we welcome you new recruits here today...
...proud that you have answered the call to service and today join the ranks of New York’s finest.
You have earned the distinction of being the best trained and best prepared police officers in the world, ready to serve and protect the most vibrant city in the world...
...in one of the most demanding policing environments anyplace, anywhere. To whom every day brings the responsibility of keeping all New Yorkers safe from crime and the threat of terrorism. And though the city is on the very cutting edge of technology, nothing replaces your eyes and ears on the street...
...and we remain safe because of the hard work and dedication of the men and women of the New York City Police Department. Congratulations to your families, your friends...
...and congratulations to you, our new New York City police officers!
You okay in all this, Pop?
I’m so proud of you, Jamie.
I know who she is. First woman recruit to win the sharpshooter medal. Well done.
Well, the gang’s all here, we should be getting over to O’Dells.
Joe died doing what he loved to do, Linda. Being a policeman.
Missing... where?
You bet.
So what's going on?
Long as you know you’ve got all the resources you need.
Okay, a brief statement before I take questions. I want to thank the media for keeping Teresa’s face before the public. Our task force has followed up on over 500 tips and I want to I assure you that the police department will not rest until we find this little girl.
Miguel, you’re a professional reporter and you wanna give credence to any amateur blogger with a laptop and an axe to grind?
Since I’ve been on the job, those stats are down across the board.
All due respect, Miss Lahari, none of us is worried about cost today. A 9-year-old girl is missing, the clock is ticking and it’s all about the recovery of Teresa. Just make sure you media people do your part and keep her face in front of the public before you run off chasing Tiger Woods’ latest girlfriend.
Thanks, Mayor.
We’re doing everything we can.
If you mean Detective First Grade Brian Reagan, that’s right.
Truthfully, I don’t spend a lot of time worrying about that.

I’ve never been late in my life.
I’m not an invalid, I had a hip replacement.
How you doing, Billy? Sorry to hear about Louise.
How the hell are we gonna find anybody in this mess?
She leave the rest of that dress at home?
Callahan, you old fart.
He was a horse’s ass then and he’s a horse’s ass now.
Quite the peacock, your friend.
I can’t find my Ipod.

Kitchen. And the skirt?
Dad! Over here!
And this is an improvement.
Anyway, we still have a lawyer in the family. Me?
She seems to be handling this pretty well, you being a cop.

Brian? Honey? You know the Verranzano at this hour...
Brian!
We’d have another one if these two would set a date.
Can’t be easy after watching you bury your brother.

‘scuse me, officer, aren’t you forgetting something?
And spoil all the fun?
Congratulations.
Your father said.
Sorry but second-year associates don’t get lunch. I’m lucky they let me out for this. It was amazing.
Subway’s quicker. Stay with your family. Bye everybody.

Thanks, Dad.
Don’t bust my chops, Brian.
We’ve got enough going on right now with me changing careers.
Dad, this is Officer Romano.
She won the sharpshooter medal.
I'll get you a cab.
Thanks, we were just talking about him.
Your nephew was in my class, right?
No, I didn’t know that. No kidding?
Yeah, he was.
Law school.
It’s in the blood I suppose.
It’s gonna be hard to live up to.
Brian’s Brian.

Nice speech, Mikey. But here’s the guy who could raise the rafters. Isn’t that right, Pat?
You’ll be a fine chief, Mikey, like your old man here. Just don’t let them play politics with you like they did with him. And that bum they replaced him with. It was a damn shame, Pat. Everybody thinks so.

Mom, did he say “fart?”
Grandpa, can I ride up front with the driver?

Hey, Reagan, we made it!
Congratulations, Chief Reagan.
Thank you, sir. Just wanted to say hello. -- You must be Sydney, right?
Thanks.
See you around, Reagan.

Jeez, kid, in those blues, you look just like your brother Joe.
Awful. I’m Sonny Malevsky. Joe was up in the 77th with us.
Hello to you too.
Anyway, I was just leaving. -- Be careful out there, kid.

Nine-year-old girl, Teresa Campos, didn’t come home from school -- St. Agnes up the block -- and the mother there got worried and went looking for her and the bodega owner told her he saw a couple young boys grab a pink backpack from the gutter here and run off with it.
Not yet.
This doll was found near where the backpack was. One of those ones you press it and it talks.
Anyway, the mother said she’d never seen it before.
Detective? I talk to you?
Woman there saw a white van pull away from the curb here really crazy.
Yeah, I know. She didn’t get the plates either, but she said it had a cracked back window.
She always comes home. She comes home every day. She knows her mother worries.

She’s a good girl!
Pablo is her father! There was no fight! Where is she? You have to find her!
My baby! Please, please help us!!!!!

Excuse me! My name is Professor Robert Jordan! I know where the missing little girl is!
She’s been transferred to Earth’s sister planet in the Andromeda Galaxy as of 22 hundred hours according to my last communique!
We’ll launch a rocket to check that out, sir.
My boy was sick! We were trying to get to the hospital!

Who is it?
Yeah...?
What are you doing? You can’t just barge in here.
What?
What doll?
You can’t take that! I’m not done with it yet!
I’m a reviewer for Doll World Magazine.
Y’know, you’re not supposed to bust into people’s places without a warrant! I’m gonna sue!
Chief Reagan, what do you say to blog allegations there’s a third fewer police than on the Allie Dintenfass Amber Alert on the Upper East Side last summer?

Then what’s your response to polls that show a boroughs-wide lack of faith in police by the Latino community and a slow and steady rise in crime there?
Then you’re saying that the mayor’s budgetary cutbacks aren’t affecting the department’s ability to keep all citizens of this city safe?

Y’know, I was also your brother Joe’s training officer when he was a new boot.
Good guy, your brother.
I hear you went to Harvard.
That right? So what are you doing on the beat? Seeing how the real people live? Writing a book?
You know, Harvard, that’s something we’re gonna have to find out.
Terrible thing about your brother. He was a great cop.
You got that right. ‘cause, you know, just ‘cause your old man’s the chief I’m not going to cut you any slack. You’re going to have to earn it just like everybody else.
Now, your brother Brian, on the other hand...
Harvard, I get the last word, okay?
That’s us.

Who is it?
Can I help you?
Yes, but he’s not here.
I don’t know.
We’re separated and I’m divorcing the bastard and I haven’t seen him in months. What is this about?
Has he done something wrong? What do you want him for?
Ronnie?
I sent him a box of his winter clothes a couple weeks ago.
The Lincoln Inn in Yonkers, but I don’t know if he’s still there.

Caught the news conference. Nice job.
You know, Mike, we gotta find this kid. Alive.
That better be good enough. I hear your boy is lead detective.
Think that’s wise, Mike? Could be exposing yourself to all kinds of scrutiny if it goes south. You’re popular with the public but I don’t have to tell you you don’t have a lot of friends in high places to back you up.
Well, maybe you should.
And another thing, that bit just now on TV about since you’ve been chief and the crime stats decreasing? There’s no future in that kind of grandstanding. Just ask your old man.

Drop it! Now!
You can do that? Do it!
Container was empty when I got here.
No!
Everybody shut up!
Please!

We speeding, Officer? Bad joke. Not everyday you get pulled over by a Navy cruiser.
Below deck. I’m James Meyer, first mate. What can I do you for?
He’s a little busy captaining right now. He’ll be up soon. Maybe I can help.
Sure. Inclement weather ahead, we’re trying to avoid it.
Comm’s on the fritz. That’s what the captain’s working on.
Yeah...I’m sorry. Feel like we’re not on the same page. What’s this about?
He in some kind of trouble?
Holy crap.
Skipper gonna be okay?
I can’t believe this is happening.
Skipper doesn’t have problems. Everyone loves him.
Holy crap.
Willis was drowned in the head?
We need to speak. Alone.
Holy--
I have no--
Renaldo? He’s--
Twenty.
I think six or seven...
He told us to be quiet.
Mess Deck...all right? Now let’s just...
She’s bleeding, man. Can’t stop it.
By threatening to shoot her?
Come on, man! Let go of--
We heard that gunshot before. We were sure you were dead.
They took her right after Aranda grabbed you.

Don’t answer.
Can’t think! Turn it down!
No talking!
I said shut up!
What the hell are you doing!
No talking!
I can.
Who says it’s a threat?
He’s gone. Now it’s me.
Attention, USS Serano... This is the San Dominick...
We want ten million dollars in unmarked bills delivered in one
hour’s time. Or we will shoot a hostage and toss them overboard.
Now, you have fifty-nine minutes.
You have the money?
You’re stalling and it won’t work.
I don’t need a boat. This isn’t a negotiation, it’s a demand. Blood’s on your hands now.
On your feet.
Get up now!
Wanna take her place?
Now you have the money?
Unbelievable! Still stalling. Still trying to trick me. The only way 
you’ll take me seriously is with a bullet.
You and how many snipers?
I’m supposed to believe you?
You’re wrong, though. Your man’s going to be hurt.
And I’m making an example of him.
Enough. Say goodbye.
Now. Because I have the power. And you people only respect power.
So I’m going to use that power and--
That’s all you’re gonna do?
I’m okay. Stay where you are. Understood?
I don’t know--
Vilandro was the real leader. Outfitted us. Got us fake papers.
Take the boat out of port. Contact the shipping company for ransom...
We get our money and an escape boat meets us. Simple. Clean.
Vilandro went to the radio room with the captain. They fought. Everything fell apart.
You think you’re in control now. Because you have me. But you’re
wrong. When the others--
Deck Four. Vilandro sent him to guard a shipping container down
there. Right before he got in the fight with the captain. I don’t
know why... I swear!
What are you waiting for? Help me!
Jaime? What happened to you?
My insurance policy.
He probably got lost somewhere down here. But this is the container...
Empty, huh? What a joke.
Is that a bomb?
Just to be clear, that’s not our bomb... As soon as you and your people
leave the ship.
I told you, it’s not our bomb.
No idea. But it’s going off one way or another.
Don’t trust him, Jaime. He’s a federal. They’ll send us to Guantanamo. You want that?
Smart man wouldn’t be here.
The only thing we wanted was ransom. Then the escape boat comes and we go home...
Yes. And it will be here soon.
What are you saying?
Jaime, listen to him. There’s no boat. No way out... You need to give up.
What are you doing? Defuse it!

Trying, Sir... Can’t seem to stop the bleeding. Feeling dizzy.
Petty Officer Felton.
Patricia...
What...
I’ve had better days, Sir.
Shoot him, Sir. I’ll take my chances.

My boys are in there!
I don't see them...
Chris, baby -- where's Emmett?
He's only 7. I told him never to open the door for anyone... Let me go!
If you came over to apologize...
My baby died, that's what happened.
You don't have kids, do you?
So you're right, you can't understand.
You probably think you did me a favor.
Emmett was 7. Small for his age, but so smart --
He would've known something bad was happening...
This doesn't make any sense.
This was a good building. Hardworking people just trying to get up and out.
That's right. Except -- Goddamn Felton Ames.
Scumbag dealer who lived downstairs.
He wouldn't get his hands dirty. Man thinks he's Scarface: fancy suits,
fools with guns taking him around.
We tried to kick him out, but the landlord wouldn't do it. Said he paid his rent in cash...
You should've let me die in there.

I'm not MS-13.
Do I look like one of those guys with face tattoos and the crazy eyes?
All I do is work. Every day.
Metapan.
My parents died. I have a younger brother -- had to leave him with our little sisters...
Three.
I'm sure it was MS. That's exactly why I stay away from those guys.
I told you --
What the hell are you drawing?

I'm not dragging this out.
No, you can't. There's no prison, no special unit, where they can't get to me.
I'm gonna die in jail no matter what. If I tell you anything, I'm dead the
day I arrive. Like Wilmer. If I don't talk, you put me away, I
could live inside another 40 years. And that's still better than where I came from.

Guys were in early, getting ready for a basketball tournament -- and
one of them found it in a gym bag under the bleachers.
I've only been director here for a few months, but -- no friggin' clue.
I grew up down the street, was career Army, just moved back.
I would've preferred Florida, but my mom's had a diner here 40 years. I
took this job to stay close.
She gets robbed all the time, got beat up... 73 year old woman.
I start and end my days there, try to keep an eye on her.
What? She points at one of the players --
Look, I'm not bucking for a Nobel Peace Prize, I just don't deal with
their crap. They can get along or stay out of my gym.
Come on, this tournament was planned way before any bombs were going off.
You kidding? It's hard enough dealing with the black gangs. Closest I've
got is a Mexican kid working as a handyman.
You served?
Yeah, well -- ditto.
They pay you extra for dragging this affirmative action baby around?
I can tell you everything. But -- you have to drop all the charges against me.
I can't leave my mother alone with the animals in the South Bronx.
I'm serious.
Who's she?
What are you talking about?
Ma...
Please, don't do this --
And I passed them to Bernardo, with the bombs. He had runners plant them.
Lawrence had me give it directly to a runner after Bernardo got caught.
He had a list: housing projects the big drug gangs run in the Bronx.
Millbrook. But he might not be bringing down a building this time.
Nothing, I swear. We just -- The only other thing, I told him:
the cellphone battery's cheap, dies fast. It only has enough power to
work as a trigger for about 24 hours. The last bomb's packed with nails.

Emmett Grant at the 20, 15, 10...
It's too late, he's gone! Touchdown!
I'm not a baby. We're gonna eat meatball sandwiches and play Xbox.
It's not gonna be a minute.
Do I get to be the Patriots all night?

But wait, the big man's on his tail...
Just 'til my mom gets home.
We are. You go get us set, and I'll be up in a minute -- okay, Em?
First game, then we'll see.
So... what're you doing?
Graphing equations? Kind of.

So you're... babysitting?
Going home to work on our algebra,
but -- I don't really get it. Do you?
Can you show me?

Where’s your brother and sister?
Funny really. Your mother always used to scold me for spending so much on wine. “All tastes the same after a few glasses”. She was probably right.
She would have been mad at me for buying this lot.
See you at lunch then.
Are you happy with it?
Well then- if you’re happy... I’m happy.
I think I've got it covered. Thanks.
One glass before lunch time. That’s what you always said was on the right side of respectable.
I’m doing the right thing. You’d have agreed with me, wouldn’t you...?
There’s some developments I need to discuss with you after lunch-
This is something that needs to be done.

Don’t worry- I’ve got this covered.
I didn’t realise there was a dress code.
Yeah. Probably by some six year old boy in a sweatshop somewhere.
Maybe it's better we wait up at the house.
Well, I saw him after the boat delivered supplies for lunch-
Which doesn’t make it morally right. Ask the hundreds of people made homeless by Dad’s little ‘loopholes’.
No - I was running...had my headphones on. Normally I have a work-out on the beach when I stay here.
But the weather looked like it was turning, so decided just to head to the gym instead.
Um- no- Rosie saw me.
Yes.
It was just practice- I mean- I have a pistol, yes- but it’s for personal protection. I’ve got the papers for it.
In a lock box in my room. It’s quite safe.
I keep the key on me at all times.
All times.
But if dad was killed by a shotgun-
Yeah. Not a fan of guns, but I’ve been working for an aid organisation around the world.
Sadly some of the places which need the most help are also the most dangerous.
...Yeah. They- they understand.
That’s kind of the point. You’ll have heard the stories. People being turfed out of their homes and so on.
Oh yeah. He knew how I felt.
Only a few days. I haven’t been here for a long time.
Had some pretty big issues with how dad had made his millions. Seemed better to stay away than have endless arguments about it.
But after mum died... felt it might be time to build those bridges again, y’know?
Trust me, you won’t find a better lock.
Well... yes... but Rosie saw me in the gym. And violence is never an answer to anything... I’m a pacifist.
...Maybe... maybe whoever else used it was wearing gloves or...
It was just- just your classic father-son disagreement- nothing special-
...It was a big deal. The environmental damage alone would have been catastrophic...
Sure... I got angry. I wasn’t going to hold back. But he told me not to worry. He had decided not to go ahead with it.
Yeah. Said he’d been thinking a lot since mum died. That he needed to make changes to his life. Big changes. That would affect us all.
I don’t know. He just told me that he knew I would be alright. And that he was... he was proud of me.
I told you. It's a dangerous job-
...It's not relevant.
Look- I had my own problems- got in a little deep and upset the wrong people.
I got arrested in Darfur at a checkpoint. Drug possession. It was a tiny amount... But that didn’t seem to count for much. Plea bargained my way out of jail- by giving up the names of the dealers. They weren’t happy. At all. I wasn’t lying when I said the pistol was for protection.
I know how it looks but... I’ve seen enough people arrested from crimes they didn’t commit... enough injustice...
I just know when you get the chance... you run if you have to.
You set me up.

No. I think she would’ve just been happy to have everyone together again.
Ma’am...?
Mr. Jackson...?
Yes. I - I heard it. I was preparing lunch.
I was preparing the vegetables for lunch. Still had another thirty minutes before everything had to be ready so this would have been around 11:40.
I thought it was just Mr. Jackson shooting the birds again.
Uh- yes- I did see him in the gym-
Maybe around half past eleven...
...all the way through to eleven fifty, twelve...
Well - I was busy going in and out the kitchen but I’m fairly sure I’d have noticed if he’d gone anywhere else.
Thought you might want something to keep you going.
He’d sometimes be in here till all hours. Wasn’t scared of a little hard work, that’s for sure.
Of course.
I’m not. There’s really... nothing to say.
I brought the items you asked for. Brush. Cocoa powder.
He's very good.
No- no- imitation-
No- I swear-
...It was a gift.
From Mr. Jackson.
I'm fine, Mr. Jackson. Can't be sitting down on the job.
I know, sir.
Really- no thank you- Mr. Jackson-
...he wouldn't. Doesn't seem like him.

It’s my mother. Swimming. She used to love doing laps in the pool.
It’s not a physical representation. It’s more... my memory of what it felt like to watch her.
Daddy? I’ve almost finished it.
What do you think?
Yes. I think I am.
Good idea boys. Let’s start bickering- today of all days.
Could you check where my father is. Some of us are getting hungry.
Actually we were just waiting for you. We'd like to move our father inside now.
I saw him when I was painting by the swimming pool.
I was by the pool, working on my painting. I heard the shot- assumed the same thing as Rosie. The birds.
...It’s... it’s not the only gun.
Yesterday afternoon, I was out looking for inspiration... and I heard some shots.
...I’m sorry. But it worried me. Me and Terrance were going to speak to you about it.
Here we go.
Ssh. Listen.
I forget how violent these storms can be. That primal force of nature. If I could capture just some of that in one of my paintings...
Oh yes. It's my biggest dream.
Well, I have turned my hand to a number of things, yes. When the muse calls, one tends to follow.
Being a painter isn't a real job?
Oh he’s always been very supportive of me.
I'm sure he'd try to.
What you said was right- he was very business minded. When I wanted to pursue the arts- my dreams- rather than join the family firm...
Five minutes. That’s all I ever wanted. Five minutes for him to sit and read something I’d written or look at a painting I’d done- I mean, really look- not just glance and dismiss it...
Not just glance and dismiss... me.
Look- did I have issues with my father? Yes. Yes I did. But I didn’t kill him. I have issues with everyone.
My brothers. My mother. If we keep talking I’ll probably have issues with you two.
But it's okay. I'm in therapy for it.
This is why I could never leave New York.
I thought Joseph... I thought he'd been arrested for it already...?
...I don't know...
...I'm not sure I understand.
Dad never mentioned anything about this...

Right. Yeah. I can see that now-
Absolutely.
The colours are really nice.
Ah- Mr. Jackson- these are the faxes from the London office- the documents you requested.
I’m Emily Adamson. I’m Mr. Jackson’s personal assistant.
Yes. The housemaid- Rosie- she found the um...
Yes... of course...
Mr. Jackson's two sons and his daughter.
It's been a year since Mrs. Jackson passed away.
A stroke. It was very sudden. Mr. Jackson wanted everyone in the family to join him here to remember her.
Me? No. He had some work things he wanted me to go over this weekend.
Mr. Jackson liked to do things his own way. I mean, take a look at this island. No internet, no mobile reception- only one landline. He doesn’t even own a computer. Used to call this place his ‘Fortress of Solitude’.
He made sure of that- security was very important to him.
No- I saw him later in his study- he was just putting something in the safe. Then headed out for a walk- it was around 11.20 or so...
I’m not sure. Financial projections maybe.
He did seem a little preoccupied.
It’s not my place but... maybe today you shouldn’t be worrying about business.
He runs a multi-million pound business. There’s always something on his mind.
Yes. Of course.
Just his daily routine.
I was in my room... taking a shower, getting ready for lunch.
These are all of Alexander's files that were in storage.
Combination is his wedding anniversary.
No. He didn't mention it. I imagine it was routine.
No. That's them all.
Absolutely.
Honestly, that's all we've got here.
It happens a lot out here...
Thank you.
...Oh.
My father had a small boat hire business- Alexander crushed it.
The anger and stress of it killed him.
I started working for him, just after his wife died. And... he wasn’t the man I thought he was going to be. He was... I don’t know... broken, I guess..
By his wife's passing. By how he reached out to his children... and to see how they barely cared.
More like disgusted. Realised how alone he really was.
That's true. I don't think I forgive Mr. Jackson. But it was like he'd been punished enough.
The money is good. If you're loyal to him... you're paid well. Revenge doesn't pay the bills.
I guess everybody's got a price.
...I don't know. I mean, you wouldn't...
How could you - ?!

I don’t know what to say. Lisa was
a good person. But if you’re here
because you think I had something
to do with it --
Actually, no, I didn’t.
(then)
I asked her about all the plastic
surgery she’d had.
She’d undergone a rhinoplasty and a
breast augmentation. I couldn’t
understand why an already beautiful
woman would change her appearance
so drastically, so I asked her
about it. She thought it was some
sort of come-on --
I helped organize a fundraiser for
the hospital two years ago, back
before the surgeries. I know I
still have the pictures...
There. That’s a picture I took of
Lisa and Dr. Mantlo that night.
Tell me you wouldn’t want to ask
why she did it.
I asked my neighbor out. Twice,
she said no. The third time, she
called the police. Total
overreaction on her part. She
apologized and dropped the charges.
I was home. Sleeping. Alone. No,
that’s not much of an alibi, but
I’m not worried. Know why?
Because I didn’t do it.

I’m sorry. I can see why you might
think it was the same guy... I just
don’t think I can help you.
No. I came in through my front
door and he was just... there.
I don’t think so...I don’t think so...
I don’t know. I mean... he was on
top of me so quickly. His hands
were around my throat...
What about it?
Ski --
I think I’d like you to leave now.
Get out.

...her name is Lisa. When I see
her, I get these feelings and I...
Please, Dr. Mantlo. You need to
help me. You need to tell me how
to stop myself from hurting her.

Murder...
Mystery...
The macabre.
What is it about a dark and stormy night that sets our pulses racing? What is it about a hard-boiled detective, a femme fatale, and the cold steel of a gun that keeps our bedside lamps glowing until the wee hours of the morning?
However the spell is cast, tonight we honor one of the masters of the form and celebrate the launch of “Storm’s End,” the stunning conclusion to his best-selling Derrick Storm mystery series.
Ladies and gentlemen, the Master of the Macabre... Nick Castle.
Pig.
What kind of idiot kills off a best-selling main character?
Is that what you're doing? Punishing me by killing the golden goose?
Then for godsakes why?
You don't kill a billion dollar franchise because you're bored.
God forbid you work. You could've retired him, crippled him, had him join a frickin' circus! But no. You put a bullet through his head.
Oh I don't know. The fact the new book was due nine weeks ago?
I’m not hearing genius, Nick. I’m hearing blockage. I’m hearing you haven’t written in months.
My sources are very reliable.
They better be, because Storm or no Storm, you’re still under contract. And if I don’t have a manuscript on my desk in the next three weeks, Black Pawn is prepared to demand the return of your advance.
Try me, Cortez. Just try me.
He gets about a thousand letters a week.
Nick? He only wants the ones with naked pictures. We send a form letter to the rest.
You've met the man. He positively inspires death threats.
Why aren't you writing?
Because you answered the phone. Now when am I going to see some pages?
Really, Nick? Fake reception loss?
Are you really Nick Castle?

Apartment 217.
This'll take hours.
No, ma'am.
Maintenance found her about forty minutes ago.
Kendra Philips. She lives in the building.

Beckett. Figured they'd send you down.
Cuz. You like the freaky ones.
Allison Tisdale. 24. Grad student in Social Work at NYU.
Her father's money. Upper east side. Real estate.
No forced entry. No sign of theft. No sign of struggle. She must've known the guy.
What are you thinking?
Unless you're a genuine psycho.
Familiar, how?
DNA and prints are negative, just like Fisk. Guy was careful.
Other than your boy there, no.
Maybe he likes you.
You know in "Dead Man's Chest," when those fishermen find that body stuffed in a crabpot?
How do you come up with that stuff?
